04749nam a22007095i 9780824863289DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20072007hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248632897 a10.1515/97808248632892doi  a(DE-B1597)483814  a(OCoLC)256492568  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aREL0070102bisacsh0483pa290qDE-1011 aMcAra, Sally, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLand of Beautiful Vision :bMaking a Buddhist Sacred Place in New Zealand /cSally McAra. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b21 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTopics in Contemporary Buddhism ;v1500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editor’s Preface -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Spelling and Transliteration -- tIntroduction -- t1 .A New Tradition -- t2. Unplugging from the Grid -- t3. A Spiritual Home -- t4. Unsettling Place -- t5. The Stūpa Is Dhardo -- t6. Interanimation -- t7. ‘‘Re-visioning’’ Place -- tAppendix 1. FWBO Figures -- tAppendix 2. The Five Precepts -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tSources Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLand of Beautiful Vision is the first book-length ethnography to address the role of material culture in contemporary adaptations of Buddhism and the first to focus on convert Buddhists in New Zealand. Sally McAra takes as her subject a fascinating instance of an ongoing creative process whereby a global religion is made locally meaningful through the construction of a Buddhist sacred place. She uses an in-depth case study of a small religious structure, a stupa, in rural New Zealand to explore larger issues related to the contemporary surge in interest in Buddhism and religious globalization. Her research extends beyond the level of public discourse on Buddhism to investigate narratives of members of the Friends of the Western Buddhist Order (FWBO) about their relationship with the land, analyzing these and the FWBO’s transformative project through a thematic focus on key symbolic landmarks at their site, Sudarshanaloka. In considering cross-cultural interactions resulting in syncretism or indigenization of alien religions, many anthropological studies concentrate on the unequal power relations between colonizing and colonized peoples. McAra extrapolates from this literature to look at a situation where the underlying power relations are quite different. She focuses on individuals in an organization whose members seek to appropriate knowledge from an "Eastern" tradition to remake their own society—one shaped by its unresolved colonizing past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aBuddhismzNew ZealandzThames. 0aBuddhist convertszNew ZealandzThames. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486328940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824863289423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824863289.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SS